## 1. The Headline, As of July 3, 2026

Two things define the Pennsylvania individual market right now, and both are **unresolved**, not settled history:

- **The federal enhanced premium tax credits (EPTC) expired December 31, 2025**, and Congress has not restored them. The House passed a three-year "clean" extension 230–196 on January 8, 2026; as of the most recent reporting available, the **Senate has not voted on it**, and a separate bipartisan compromise (reported informally as a "CARE Act" — a shorter extension paired with income caps and fraud safeguards) was under negotiation but not enacted (Ballotpedia News, 2026; Managed Healthcare Executive, 2026). *(High confidence that EPTC lapsed and the House bill is stalled; Moderate confidence, forward-looking, on what — if anything — the Senate does next.)*
- **Pennsylvania's own FY2026–27 state budget missed its constitutional June 30, 2026 deadline** — the fifth consecutive late budget. As of this writing, no budget has been signed; Senate Republican leaders said they expect a deal "in the days following July 4th," while House Democratic leaders were less optimistic (Spotlight PA, 2026; 90.5 WESA, 2026). Last year's impasse (FY2025–26) ran 135 days late and wasn't signed until November 12, 2025 (Pennsylvania Senate Republicans, 2026). **This directly matters to your premium**, because it means the state's own relief valve — the Act 54 State Health Insurance Exchange Affordability Program — remains unfunded with no fixed date for resolution. *(High confidence on the missed deadline; Forward-looking on resolution timing.)*

In short: the two mechanisms that could most directly lower your 2026 premium — a federal subsidy restoration and a state subsidy stack — are both still pending, not enacted, as of July 2026.

