## 3. Geography Still Drives Your Bill

Pennsylvania prices individual-market plans across nine rating areas, and where you live continues to be one of the biggest predictors of both your premium and your odds of losing your carrier's network entirely.

- **Rural counties are being hit hardest, proportionally.** Juniata and Fulton counties show the steepest reported disenrollment, tied to some of the largest premium spikes in the state. Rural rating areas also rely on the thinnest carrier competition — parts of north-central PA (Elk, Cameron, Potter counties) are served by essentially two carrier families.
- **Urban counties lost the most people in raw numbers.** Philadelphia and Allegheny counties reportedly account for the largest absolute coverage losses, even though their percentage declines were smaller than the hardest-hit rural counties.
- **Carrier behavior diverged sharply.** Ambetter (Centene) received the largest approved increase in the state; Partners Insurance Company (Jefferson Health Plans) was the only carrier approved for a rate *decrease*, tied to a narrower, more efficient network design.

*(The county- and carrier-level figures above are Moderate confidence — internally consistent across the background compilation, but not independently re-verified against PID's rate-filing database this session. If you're deciding whether to switch carriers, don't rely on a percentage from this report; pull your own quote at pennie.com.)*

