## 3.5 The Subsidy Cliff, With Real Numbers

This is what "the cliff" actually looks like, using the IRS's official contribution-percentage table and a verified real-world anchor point, not an assumed visual. It illustrates a benchmark Silver plan for an older-couple household comparable to the York County example in Section 2 — individual results vary by age, family size, and rating area, so treat the shape of the curve as the takeaway, not the exact percentages for your own household.

| Income (% of FPL) | 2025 rules — required contribution (% of income) | 2026 rules — required contribution (% of income) |
|---|---|---|
| 100% | 0% | 2.1% |
| 150% | 0% | 4.2% |
| 200% | 2% | 6.3% |
| 250% | 4% | 7.9% |
| 300% | 6% | 9.5% |
| 350% | 7.5% | 9.8% |
| 400% | 8.5% | 10.0% |
| **402%** | **8.5%** | **≈26.6%** |
| 450% | 8.5% | ≈24.6% |
| 500% | 8.5% | ≈22.1% |

**How to read this:** Under the 2021–2025 enhanced rules, required contribution rose smoothly and then *capped at 8.5% of income for good* — there was no upper income limit, so a high earner never paid more than 8.5% for the benchmark plan (Bipartisan Policy Center, 2025). Under the reverted 2026 rules, the required-contribution percentage climbs toward roughly 10% as income approaches 400% of FPL (Congressional Research Service, 2026b) — and then **eligibility for any credit disappears entirely** one dollar past 400% FPL. The 402% row is not a modeling estimate; it's the Bipartisan Policy Center's own example of a 60-year-old couple at roughly $85,000 in income paying about $22,600/year — roughly a quarter of their income — instead of the 8.5% they'd have paid a year earlier (Bipartisan Policy Center, 2025). The 450% and 500% rows extrapolate that same fixed dollar premium forward, which is why the percentage *declines* as income keeps climbing past the cliff — the dollar cost doesn't scale with income at all once you're off the subsidy entirely.

This is also a precise description of the York County mechanism in Section 2: the $7,032-to-$35,712 jump isn't gradual income-based scaling, it's what happens when a household crosses from "receives a federal subsidy" to "receives none."

