## 5. The "Preventive-to-Diagnostic" Billing Trap

This one is real and worth knowing before your next annual physical. Under the ACA, a routine preventive visit is supposed to be 100% covered. The trap doesn't usually work by rewriting that visit's own billing code — the preventive CPT code and its linked diagnosis typically stay exactly as filed. What actually happens: if you mention or seek treatment for an existing condition (e.g., your blood pressure medication) during that same visit, the provider appends a **second, separately billable evaluation-and-management (E/M) code — commonly with Modifier 25 — carrying its own diagnosis pointer** for the condition discussed. That second line item, not the preventive visit itself, is what gets applied to your deductible.

**How much this can cost you depends entirely on your plan tier:**

| Plan tier | Typical individual deductible | What the added E/M charge could cost you | Resolution strategy |
|---|---|---|---|
| Bronze | $7,500+ | The full added charge could land inside a deductible you haven't come close to meeting | Request an itemized statement; confirm a *second* CPT/E-M line with Modifier 25 was actually added, not that the preventive line itself was reclassified |
| Silver, without CSR | $1,200–$3,000 | A real, but smaller, hit | Ask the provider directly what specific condition triggered the add-on code, and whether it met the "significant, separately identifiable" threshold Modifier 25 requires — a passing mention of a stable, controlled condition often doesn't |
| Silver, with CSR (income up to 250% FPL) | As low as $0 | Usually just a small copay | Confirm your CSR-adjusted deductible (not the plan's standard deductible) was the one applied to the added charge |
| Gold | $500–$1,000 | Minimal exposure | Cross-check the add-on code against your carrier's published medical-necessity/coding guidelines before paying |

**Before your visit, ask directly: "Will this be billed as preventive only, or will you be adding a separate E/M code?"** If you're billed unexpectedly, appeal citing 28 Pa. Code § 9.725 and ask your carrier for the specific coding guideline used to justify the add-on.

