## 7. The Two Open Policy Questions That Will Decide What Happens Next

**Federal:** Will the Senate act on the House's three-year EPTC extension, or on a shorter bipartisan compromise? As of the most recent available reporting, neither has happened (Managed Healthcare Executive, 2026). *(Forward-looking — check KFF.org or Congress.gov for the current status before assuming either outcome.)*

**State:** Will the General Assembly fund the Act 54 State Health Insurance Exchange Affordability Program (targeted at households between 151%–300% FPL, explicitly barred from being used on Bronze plans) as part of whatever FY2026–27 budget eventually passes? Pennie has said the program's technical infrastructure is built and ready to deploy the moment funding arrives (Pennie, 2026), but funding requires either a Joint Underwriters Association transfer (capped at $50 million/year) or a direct General Assembly appropriation — and the entire state budget is currently stalled (Spotlight PA, 2026). *(Forward-looking.)*

Neither of these is resolved as of this report's date. Anything you read — including this document — describing a "current" premium relief program should be checked against Pennie.com before you act on it.

